<DOC><DOCNO> AP880413-0137 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-88 1252EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Glacier     04-13 0117</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Glacier,0121</SECOND><HEAD>India, Pakistan to Resume Talks Over Disputed Glacier</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government has agreed with Pakistanto reopen suspended talks on a disputed Himalayan glacieroverlooking military bases of three countries, the defense ministersaid Wednesday.   The two sides broke off negotiations over the 50-mile glacier inthe Kashmir border region almost two years ago.   Indian troops repulsed a Pakistani assault there in September,and other clashes followed in January.   Both nations view the Siachen glacier as strategic because itoverlooks Chinese, Indian and Pakistani bases in nearby valleys.   Indian Defense Secretary S.K. Bhatnagar will go to Pakistanlater this year for the new talks, according to Defense MinisterK.C. Pant.</TEXT></DOC>